              <div type="apparatus">
                  <listApp>
                      <app><note>Text from autopsy. </note></app>
                      <app loc="1-2"><note>[-? M]anies Cai / [T]ychenis “o [Eut]ycheni, forse s(ervus)” Manganaro Perrone.</note></app>
                  </listApp>
              </div>
              <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#IG">
                  <p>of Callityche, slave of (---)anie.</p>
              </div>
              <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#IG">
                  <p>di Callityche, schiava di (---)anie.</p>
              </div>
              <div type="commentary">
                  <p xml:lang="en">A gap sufficient for about 3 letters can be assumed on each line. The absence of interpuncts makes the division between the words
                      of the first line completely arbitrary, where it is proposed to identify in the first four letters the monophthongated feminine genitive of a headless nomen or gentilicium such as 
                      Fanie, Afranie, Granie, followed by the indication of servile status, to be associated with the next name. A more careful observation perhaps 
                      allows us to improve the reading of the final letter of the first line as L instead of I and so to propose the integration Cal/[lit]ychenis.</p>
              </div>
